results.content:
For example

This is thoroughly formatted note about something you want to remember. Hit Edit (at the top right) to make changes, and then Save (which will appear at the bottom right) to make your changes permanent. A preview of your formatted note will remain on screen, updating whenever you stop typing. You can include HTML tags in your note if you want, eg <p></p> for paragraphs or <h3></h3> for headers or <br/> for line breaks. Your note can contain inline $\LaTeX$ inside \$...\$ signs, or Display Mode $\LaTeX$ inside \ [...\ ] delimeters, eg \[ e^{i\pi}=-1,\quad \text{frac}=\frac{\text{num}}{\text{denom}}\]

Moving faster

Autocomplete is enabled for your rapid $TeX$ing convenience:

  • Type a slash () to start autocompleting a command
  • Type underscore twice (__) to get _{ } or caret twice (^^) to get ^{ }
  • The LaTeX Settings link (from the home page) allows you to define macros or expand the autocomplete
  • Clicking somewhere else on the screen will show/hide the Save button

Warnings:

Be careful with characters that are special to HTML, such as angle brackets: < >. If you put these symbols into your LaTeX code, definitely put spaces around them, or, if that doesn't work, use the HTML codes < > instead, which will render as < >. Also, if you want \$ signs in your text, you'll have to write them as \\$, since \$ is used to start a LaTeX region.
